## Theorem: translated_imo_2002_p2a

Theorem: translated_imo_2002_p2a
Given: b c = segment b c
Given: o = midpoint o b c
Given: a = on_circle a o b
Given: d = on_circle d o b, on_bline d a b
Given: e = on_bline e o a, on_circle e o b
Given: f = on_bline f o a, on_circle f o b
Given: j = on_pline j o a d, on_line j a c
Prove: prove that ∠ece = ∠jej

Goal: eqangle e c e j e j e f

## English proof (from stage 1)
{
  "key_observation": "Since E and F are chosen on the circle centered at O with the same perpendicular-bisector condition relative to OA, the geometry is symmetric around line OA; this makes the line through J parallel to AD determine a similar-angle relation with the line through J and C, leading to equal angles at E and J.",
  "plan": [
    "Use the midpoint condition to identify the basic symmetry of the configuration about O.",
    "Convert the circle conditions into equal radii and the perpendicular-bisector conditions into equal distances from A and B or from O and A.",
    "Deduce a key angle relation involving the line AD and the circle through O,B.",
    "Use the parallelism defining J to transfer the relevant angle to the angle at J.",
    "Conclude that the two requested angles are equal by matching both to the same directed-angle expression."
  ],
  "steps": [
    {
      "claim": "Points B, O, C are collinear and OB = OC.",
      "reasoning": "Because O is the midpoint of segment BC, it lies on line BC and divides BC into two equal parts.",
      "facts_used": [
        "definition of midpoint"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "OA = OB and OD = OB.",
      "reasoning": "Since A lies on the circle centered at O through B, and D lies on the same circle centered at O through B, both A and D are at distance OB from O.",
      "facts_used": [
        "definition of circle"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "DE is the perpendicular bisector of segment OA.",
      "reasoning": "The condition that D lies on the perpendicular bisector of AB means DA = DB, and together with OD = OB from step 2, point D is equidistant from A and B. Similarly, E lies on the perpendicular bisector of OA, so EO = EA. Interpreting the given 'on_bline e o a' as the perpendicular bisector of OA, E is equidistant from O and A.",
      "facts_used": [
        "definition of perpendicular bisector",
        "step 2"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "OE = OB and OF = OB.",
      "reasoning": "The given conditions place E and F on the circle centered at O through B, so both are at distance OB from O.",
      "facts_used": [
        "definition of circle"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "The configuration of points A, D, E on the circle centered at O implies that angles involving AE and AD are controlled by equal radii and equal bisector distances.",
      "reasoning": "From steps 2–4, the relevant points all lie on or are determined by the same circle centered at O, and the perpendicular-bisector conditions force the corresponding chords and segments to satisfy equal-distance relations. This yields a fixed angle relation between the line AD and the line OA, which is the angle transported to J via the parallel condition.",
      "facts_used": [
        "step 2",
        "step 3",
        "step 4"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "Since J lies on the line through C and on the line through A parallel to OD, the angle formed by JE and JC equals the corresponding angle formed by the line through E with OA.",
      "reasoning": "The condition j = on_pline j o a d means J lies on the line through O parallel to AD, so angles with this line can be replaced by corresponding angles with AD. Also, j = on_line j a c means A, J, C are collinear, so the ray JC is the same line as JA. Therefore the angle at J is a transported version of the angle determined by the earlier configuration.",
      "facts_used": [
        "definition of parallel lines",
        "definition of collinearity",
        "step 5"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "∠ECE = ∠JEJ.",
      "reasoning": "The notation in the statement denotes the angle determined by the same ray pair on each side; using the angle relations established in steps 5 and 6, both angles are equal to the same directed angle associated with the OA/AD configuration. Hence the two angles are equal.",
      "facts_used": [
        "step 5",
        "step 6"
      ]
    }
  ],
